    "instruction": "Using metric.csv only, aggregate the full series by cmdb_id and kpi_name. For each group compute the global P95 of the 'value' field (use all available rows for that group) and the total number of points in the full series. Then filter metric.csv to the incident window from 2024-01-19 04:13:55 UTC to 2024-01-19 04:43:55 UTC. For each group produce these columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_p95, total_points, window_count (rows in the incident window), window_max, window_mean, window_earliest_timestamp, window_latest_timestamp. Sort the results by window_max descending and return only the top 20 rows. Keep the full aggregated results saved in kernel variables for later steps but do not print full raw tables."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the previous Executor step we aggregated per-component KPIs and found sustained, large memory spikes across many services during the incident window (04:16:00 to 04:40:00 UTC). Top signals were catalogue-db, orders, shipping, queue-master, carts, carts-db, user-db, and orders-db (all with window_count=25). Trace telemetry is empty and error_logs.csv is empty, so traces cannot be used to disambiguate. We must therefore localize the root cause among the allowed service-level candidates (carts, catalogue, orders, payment, user) using metric severity and logs. Next we should (1) check for which of these candidate services their KPIs (mem, cpu, diskio, error, etc.) exceed their global P95 within the incident window, and quantify severity as window_max / global_p95 and earliest exceedance timestamp, and (2) inspect log.csv for those candidate services within the incident window to see whether error_count or other log KPIs spiked (total errors, max per-minute errors, earliest error timestamp). This will let us identify which allowed service is both anomalous by metrics and shows supporting log signals.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For the candidate services [\"carts\", \"catalogue\", \"orders\", \"payment\", \"user\"] do the following (use the aggregated per-component-kpi global thresholds previously stored or recompute by using the full metric.csv series per cmdb_id-kpi):\n1) For each candidate cmdb_id and each available kpi_name, compute: global_p95 (using full series), window_max, window_count (rows inside 2024-01-19 04:13:55 to 2024-01-19 04:43:55 UTC), earliest_timestamp_in_window, and a severity_ratio = window_max / global_p95 (if global_p95>0 else use NaN). Keep only rows where window_count>0. Return a compact table sorted by severity_ratio descending. Limit output to at most 50 rows.\n2) From log.csv, for each candidate cmdb_id within the incident window, compute: sum_errors = sum(value where log_name==\"log.error_count\"), max_error = max(value where log_name==\"log.error_count\"), earliest_error_ts (first timestamp with value>0), and total_log_rows_in_window. Also include sample log_name values present for that cmdb_id. Return one row per candidate service (max 5 rows).\nKeep outputs concise (aggregates only). Store full intermediate tables in kernel variables for later inspection but do not print raw time series."
}

Review summary: Metric analysis across the incident window (2024-01-19 04:13:55–04:43:55 UTC) shows sustained anomalies. Among allowed service candidates, carts exhibits the strongest relative deviations: cpu and tail-latency (latency-90) both exceed their global P95 (severity_ratio ≈ 1.28 and ≈ 1.21) and are sustained for the entire sampled window (first observed at 2024-01-19 04:16:00 UTC). Logs contain no error_count spikes and trace/error_logs are not available. Following the localization rules (choose the most significant service-level deviation when traces are missing), the most likely root cause is carts with high CPU usage causing elevated request latency.

